**Reviews and Follow-up**

* Decides to review measures in 18 months or sooner if necessary;
* Decides to remain seized of the matter.

**Annex I: Monitoring Team Responsibilities**

* Submit comprehensive reports on implementation by Member States;
* Assist the Ombudsperson;
* Assist the Committee in reviewing names on the Al-Qaida Sanctions List;
* Analyze reports and information from Member States;
* Assist the Committee in following up on requests to Member States;
* Submit a program of work to the Committee;
* Work closely with CTED and 1540 Committee's group of experts;
* Participate in and support activities under the UN Global Counter-Terrorism Strategy;
* Assist the Committee with analysis of non-compliance;
* Present recommendations to the Committee.
The Security Council resolution outlines the tasks of the Monitoring Team, which include:

(k) assisting the Committee in considering listing proposals by compiling and circulating relevant information and preparing draft narrative summaries;

(l) bringing to the Committee's attention new circumstances that may warrant delisting, such as information on deceased individuals;

(m) consulting with Member States before travel;

(n) coordinating with national counter-terrorism focal points;

(o) encouraging Member States to submit names and identifying information for the Al-Qaida Sanctions List;

(p) presenting additional identifying information to update the List;

(q) studying and reporting on the evolving Al-Qaida threat and recommending countermeasures;

(r) monitoring and reporting on implementation of measures, including preventing the misuse of the Internet;

(s) consulting with Member States and organizations;

(t) consulting with intelligence and security services;

(u) consulting with the private sector on the assets freeze;

(v) working with international organizations to promote awareness and compliance;

(w) facilitating assistance on capacity building;

(x) working with INTERPOL to obtain photographs of listed individuals;

(y) assisting other Security Council bodies;

(z) reporting to the Committee on its work;

(aa) submitting a written report on linkages between Al-Qaida and other listed entities;

(bb) undertaking other responsibilities identified by the Committee.
Here is a concise summary of the document:

The Office of the Ombudsperson is authorized to process delisting requests from individuals, groups, undertakings, or entities on the Al-Qaida Sanctions List.
